			<div class="post-2356 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-greece tag-capital-controls tag-greece tag-switzerland">

				<div class="entry">

					<h2><a href="http://blog.mktgeist.com/2012/05/29/capital-controls-coming-to-greece-and-switzerland-zerohedge/">Capital Controls Coming to Greece and Switzerland&nbsp;[Zerohedge]</a></h2>

					<div class="post-info">
						<p>
							<span class="time">May 29, 2012</span>
															<span class="author">by <a href="http://blog.mktgeist.com/author/mktgeistmike/" title="Posts by mktgeistmike" rel="author">mktgeistmike</a></span>
																						<span class="post-comments"><a href="http://blog.mktgeist.com/2012/05/29/capital-controls-coming-to-greece-and-switzerland-zerohedge/#respond" title="Comment on Capital Controls Coming to Greece and Switzerland&nbsp;[Zerohedge]">Leave a comment</a></span>
																				</p>
					</div>

					<p>A few weeks ago I wrote about my conversation with a friend in AthensÂ Â <a href="http://brucekrasting.blogspot.com/2012/05/surprising-conversation-with-athens.html">(Link)</a>. At the time, he believed that the June 17 election would bring a different result than the May 6 election disaster &#8211; the catalyst for change being the fear of leaving the Euro. So far he has been proven right. So I called to get an update.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div><a href="http://mktgeist.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/blomberg.png"><img src="http://mktgeist.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/blomberg.png?w=300" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>
<p><strong>.</strong></p>
<p><strong>BK</strong>Â â It seems you might be right. The polls from Greece this weekend have given the European markets a lift today. Do you still believe that the centrist parties will win sufficient votes to form a coalition government and avoid a catastrophe?</p>
<p><strong>AthensÂ </strong>â Only a fucking idiot would invest money based on these polls.</p>
<p><strong>BK</strong>Â â Are the polls not correct?<strong></strong></p>
<p><strong>Athens</strong>Â â The European leaders have scared the Greeks with their talk about throwing Greece to the wolves. So yes, I think that the fringe on the extreme left and right will not get as many votes as they did on May 6. But Syriza (anti-bailout) has gained votes. The election is a complete crapshoot.</p>
<p>It may not matter. Itâs not certain that Greece can make it to June 17 without a crisis.</p>
<p><strong>BK</strong>Â â Explain that.</p>
<p><strong>Athens</strong>Â â There is no money left in Greece. In the first two weeks of June, the government and the banks will face a huge cash squeeze. Everyday more money leaves as depositors withdraw cash and transfer money out of the country.</p>
<p>Itâs clear to everyone who lives here. Greeks are not stupid. Either exchange controls happen before the election, or they happen immediately after. The election will not change that either way.</p>
<p><strong>BK</strong>Â â What do you mean by &#8220;exchange controls?&#8221;</p>
<p><strong>AthensÂ </strong>â A ban on money transfers out of the country. Limits on the amount of cash that can be withdrawn from a bank or ATM.</p>
<p><strong>BK</strong>Â â What are the odds that this happens before June 17?</p>
<p><strong>Athens</strong>Â â The election is now twenty days away. For Greece that is a very long time. If the Europeans wanted to send a message to Greece, they would stop the emergency lending. So I would say it&#8217;s 50-50 that we see some measures before the election .</p>
<p><a href="http://www.zerohedge.com/contributed/2012-05-28/capital-controls-coming-greece-and-switzerland">Read more</a></p>
